        <link rel="schema.DC" href="https://purl.org/DC/elements/1.0/" /><meta name="citation_journal_title" content="RadioGraphics" /><meta name="dc.Title" content="Orthotopic Liver Transplantation: Reversible Doppler US Findings in the Immediate Postoperative Period" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Rupan  Sanyal" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Chandana G.  Lall" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Ramit  Lamba" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Sadhna  Verma" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Shetal N.  Shah" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Temel  Tirkes" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="William A.  Berry" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Kumaresan  Sandrasegaran" /><meta name="dc.Description" content="The typical reversible immediate post–liver transplantation Doppler US findings that may appear alarming but usually reverse within 48–72 hours are discussed." /><meta name="Description" content="The typical reversible immediate post–liver transplantation Doppler US findings that may appear alarming but usually reverse within 48–72 hours are discussed." /><meta name="dc.Description" content="Orthotopic liver transplantation (OLT) is the only definitive treatment for irreversible acute liver failure and chronic liver disease. In the immediate postoperative period after OLT, patients are..." /><meta name="Description" content="Orthotopic liver transplantation (OLT) is the only definitive treatment for irreversible acute liver failure and chronic liver disease. In the immediate postoperative period after OLT, patients are..." /><meta name="dc.Publisher" content="Radiological Society of North America" /><meta name="dc.Date" scheme="WTN8601" content="2011-12-30" /><meta name="dc.Type" content="research-article" /><meta name="dc.Format" content="text/HTML" /><meta name="dc.Identifier" scheme="publisher-id" content="115006" /><meta name="dc.Identifier" scheme="doi" content="10.1148/rg.321115006" /><meta name="dc.Source" content="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.32